re-time guess.\n\n### Signal 1: Observed Branch Counts\n\nAcross all turns in a session, count which branches or stack branches were\nobserved while the user was working.\n\nExample:\n\n- `main` observed a few times\n- `my-feature` observed many more times\n\nThat may indicate the user started prompting while still on `main`, then moved\nto `my-feature`. This is useful, but weak on its own because a GitButler\nworktree can hav\n[TRUNCATED]\n the next agent interaction,\nthe commit belongs to the interval between two observed capture turns. Do not\ncreate a fake empty capture turn to represent it. Store the real capture turn\nsnapshots and derive the interval evidence later.\n\nIf there is no later captured turn yet, read-time scoring may compare the latest\ncaptured worktree files against the currently queried branch, change, or PR\ncommits. Treat that as current-repo derived evidence, not as a stored historical\nobservation.\n\n### Signal 3: Direct Target Observations\n\nDirect target observations are stronger than branch counts. Examples:\n\n- a branch in the capture turn snapshot carries the queried review id or pull\n  request\n- a commit in the capture turn snapshot carries the queried change id\n- a branch in the capture turn snapshot has the queried branch name\n\nThese still are not durable ownership claims. They mean \"this target was visible\nin the repository state around this capture turn.\"\n\n### Automatic Scoring\n\nThe preferred product direction is no required human confirmation. Capture\nstores observations and lookup indexes. Read paths compute an association score\nand show related sessions automatically when confidence is high enough.\n\nDo not persist automatic scoring results as durable relationships in v1. They\nshould be derived read-time results with a scoring version, confidence label,\nscore, and highlighted turn keys. A future cache is fine if it is explicitly\nrebuildable derived data.\n\nSuggested result shape:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"sessi